{
  "cells": [
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "---\n",
        "title: \"Working with Python and Chatlas\"\n",
        "date: \"2026-01-28\"\n",
        "date-modified: \"2026-03-17\"\n",
        "version: \"2.0\"\n",
        "description: \"Using Python and Chatlas to interact with AI assistants via the OpenAI API.\"\n",
        "categories: [python, chatlas, api, openai, workflow]\n",
        "format:\n",
        "  html:\n",
        "    toc: true\n",
        "    code-fold: false\n",
        "execute:\n",
        "  eval: false\n",
        "  echo: true\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "# Overview\n",
        "\n",
        "This vignette provides information about using Python and [Chatlas](https://posit-dev.github.io/chatlas/) to interact with AI assistants. It describes the conceptual role of each step in a typical API conversation workflow, and documents less-common techniques not covered in the conversation templates. For working code for routine tasks, see the template conversation files in `conversations/`.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create a Virtual Environment\n",
        "\n",
        "Before working with Python packages, you need a virtual environment. See one of the following vignettes depending on your setup:\n",
        "\n",
        "- `vignettes/venv-virtual-environments.qmd` — standard Python `venv` approach\n",
        "- `vignettes/uv-virtual-environments.qmd` — modern `uv` approach, recommended for cross-machine workflows\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# Install Packages\n",
        "\n",
        "See `vignettes/venv-virtual-environments.qmd` or `vignettes/uv-virtual-environments.qmd` for full installation instructions and package management guidance.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# Standard Conversation Workflow\n",
        "\n",
        "The sections below describe the conceptual role of each step in a typical API conversation. The specific packages, models, file paths, and helper functions in use at any given time can change, so the working code lives in the template conversation files in `conversations/` rather than here.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Load Packages\n",
        "\n",
        "Every conversation document begins by loading the Python packages it depends on. This typically includes packages for interacting with the API (e.g., `openai`, `chatlas`), managing credentials (e.g., `keyring`), handling file paths and dates, and any local helper packages. Keeping all imports at the top of the document makes dependencies explicit and makes it easy to spot when a package needs to be installed.\n",
        "\n",
        "## File Paths and Environment Variables\n",
        "\n",
        "Declaring file paths, environment variables, and the model name near the top of the conversation document — rather than inline throughout the code — makes the document easier to reuse and adapt. When you need to point the conversation at a different file or switch models, there is a single place to make that change. This section typically sets today's date, paths to any prompt templates or input files, and the model identifier.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Load Helper Functions\n",
        "\n",
        "Many conversations rely on local helper functions stored in a shared Python package within the repo. Loading these functions near the top of the document, after packages and file paths, keeps the rest of the conversation clean and focused on the task rather than implementation details.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Expose API\n",
        "\n",
        "API keys should never be hardcoded in a script or committed to Git. The standard approach in this repo is to store keys in the system keyring and retrieve them at runtime, then set them as environment variables for the duration of the session. This section handles that retrieval and confirms the key was found before proceeding. See `vignettes/keyring.qmd` for setup instructions.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Read the Template Prompt\n",
        "\n",
        "When using a prompt template stored in `prompts/`, this step reads the template file, extracts the system prompt and user message sections separately, and injects any dynamic values (e.g., lesson name, course name) using placeholder substitution. Keeping the prompt definition in a separate file — rather than inline in the conversation — makes prompts easier to version, review, and reuse.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Pass the Template Prompt to the AI Assistant\n",
        "\n",
        "This step submits the system prompt and initial user message to the API to open the conversation. The model's response to this first message is typically a confirmation that it has received and understood the instructions rather than substantive content — it establishes the context for the rest of the conversation. See [OpenAI's prompt engineering guide](https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/prompt-engineering?lang=python#message-roles-and-instruction-following) for background on message roles.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Pass Text File Contents to the AI Assistant\n",
        "\n",
        "After the conversation is initialized with the template prompt, this step passes the actual content to be worked on — typically a lesson file, draft, or document — as the next user message. The file is read as plain text and submitted directly. This is the most reliable approach for Quarto and Markdown files, which are not supported as native file uploads by the API (see [Pass a File to the API](#pass-a-file-to-the-api) below for alternatives when plain text is insufficient).\n",
        "\n",
        "## Write Output to a File for Review\n",
        "\n",
        "After receiving a response, this step writes the model's output to a Markdown file in a designated review folder. Saving the output as a file — rather than just printing it — makes it easier to review, diff against the original, and incorporate into the project. The filename typically includes today's date to make outputs easy to sort and identify later.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Follow-up and Refinement\n",
        "\n",
        "Most conversations benefit from at least one follow-up exchange after the initial response. This step is intentionally open-ended: you might ask for revisions, request a different format, probe an unclear point, or ask for a summary. Two useful patterns are creating a fork of the chat object before sending a speculative follow-up (so you can discard it without losing the main thread), and using the interactive chat interface (`chat.app()`) for rapid back-and-forth during refinement.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Save Chat History\n",
        "\n",
        "Saving the full conversation history at the end of a session makes it possible to return to the conversation later, audit what was sent and received, or pass the history back to the model in a future session for continuity. The conversation templates export history in Markdown format for readability and in JSON format for programmatic use. Optionally, you can condense a long history by asking the model to summarize it before saving, which reduces the token cost of reloading it in a future session.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Render to HTML\n",
        "\n",
        "Rendering the conversation document to HTML produces a readable, shareable record of the full session — prompts, code, and outputs together. This is useful for documentation, review, and reproducibility. Render via the Preview button in Positron or by running `quarto render path/to/conversation.qmd` in the terminal.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# Pass a File to the API\n",
        "\n",
        "The standard workflow above passes file contents as plain text, which works well for most cases. There are situations, however, where you need to pass the file itself — for example, when working with PDFs or other binary formats that cannot be read as plain text.\n",
        "\n",
        "See the OpenAI documentation for full guidance:\n",
        "\n",
        "- <https://platform.openai.com/docs/quickstart#analyze-images-and-files>\n",
        "- <https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/pdf-files>\n",
        "\n",
        "::: callout-important\n",
        "Only specific file formats are supported for direct upload. Common supported formats include `.md`, `.pdf`, `.txt`, `.py`, `.json`, `.html`, `.yaml`, and others — see the OpenAI docs for the complete list.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Quarto (`.qmd`) is not supported.** Workarounds:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Pass the file contents as plain text (the standard approach above).\n",
        "2. Convert the Quarto file to PDF before uploading.\n",
        "3. Add the file to a vector store (see [Vector Stores](#vector-stores) below) — best when the file will be referenced repeatedly.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## Upload and Use a File\n"
      ],
      "id": "cb1ee6c0"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "from openai import OpenAI\n",
        "\n",
        "client = OpenAI()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Step 1: Upload the file\n",
        "file = client.files.create(\n",
        "    file=open(\"path/to/your-file.pdf\", \"rb\"),\n",
        "    purpose=\"user_data\"\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"Uploaded file ID: {file.id}\")"
      ],
      "id": "0e03a6ed",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Step 2: Use the uploaded file as input in a conversation\n",
        "response = client.responses.create(\n",
        "    model=model,\n",
        "    input=[\n",
        "        {\n",
        "            \"role\": \"user\",\n",
        "            \"content\": [\n",
        "                {\n",
        "                    \"type\": \"input_file\",\n",
        "                    \"file_id\": file.id,\n",
        "                },\n",
        "                {\n",
        "                    \"type\": \"input_text\",\n",
        "                    \"text\": \"Please summarize the main points of this document.\",\n",
        "                }\n",
        "            ]\n",
        "        }\n",
        "    ]\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "print(response.output_text)"
      ],
      "id": "3cacc66b",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "::: callout-note\n",
        "Uploaded files persist in your OpenAI account until deleted. If you are uploading the same file repeatedly across sessions, consider reusing the file ID rather than re-uploading each time. File IDs can be found in the [OpenAI dashboard](https://platform.openai.com/storage/files) or stored locally for reuse.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# Vector Stores\n",
        "\n",
        "A vector store lets you upload files once, index them semantically, and query them across multiple chat sessions using the `file_search` tool. This is the right approach when you want a document to serve as persistent, reusable context — as opposed to passing it fresh on every call.\n",
        "\n",
        "## When to Use a Vector Store\n",
        "\n",
        "- You have a document (or set of documents) you'll query repeatedly\n",
        "- You want to ask questions grounded in specific file content\n",
        "- You need deterministic, source-traceable retrieval\n",
        "- The document is too large to pass as plain text in each call\n",
        "\n",
        "## Setup\n",
        "\n",
        "Vector stores are created and managed through the [OpenAI developer dashboard](https://platform.openai.com/storage):\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Open the dashboard and navigate to Storage.\n",
        "2. Create a new vector store and give it a name.\n",
        "3. Upload your files and wait for indexing to complete (status will show as \"ready\").\n",
        "4. Copy the vector store ID — you'll use it in your code.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Query a Vector Store\n"
      ],
      "id": "a0c100a6"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "from chatlas import ChatOpenAI\n",
        "\n",
        "chat = ChatOpenAI(model=model)\n",
        "\n",
        "vs_id = \"your-vector-store-id\"\n",
        "\n",
        "# Ask a question grounded in the uploaded documents\n",
        "resp = chat.chat(\n",
        "    \"Using ONLY the uploaded documents, answer the following question: \"\n",
        "    \"[your question here]. \"\n",
        "    \"If the answer is not explicitly stated in the documents, say so.\",\n",
        "    kwargs={\n",
        "        \"tools\": [{\"type\": \"file_search\", \"vector_store_ids\": [vs_id]}]\n",
        "    }\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "print(str(resp))"
      ],
      "id": "41962629",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Request Sources\n",
        "\n",
        "To verify which parts of the document the model used to generate its response:\n"
      ],
      "id": "baa75640"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "resp = chat.chat(\n",
        "    \"[your question here]\",\n",
        "    kwargs={\n",
        "        \"tools\": [{\"type\": \"file_search\", \"vector_store_ids\": [vs_id]}],\n",
        "        \"include\": [\"file_search_call.action.sources\"],\n",
        "    }\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "print(str(resp))"
      ],
      "id": "b42dd036",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Multi-turn Conversations with a Vector Store\n",
        "\n",
        "To keep `file_search` available across multiple turns, pass the same `kwargs` on each call — or set it once at the chat level:\n"
      ],
      "id": "7c11bd68"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Option 1: pass kwargs on each turn\n",
        "resp1 = chat.chat(\"First question\", kwargs={\"tools\": [{\"type\": \"file_search\", \"vector_store_ids\": [vs_id]}]})\n",
        "resp2 = chat.chat(\"Follow-up question\", kwargs={\"tools\": [{\"type\": \"file_search\", \"vector_store_ids\": [vs_id]}]})\n",
        "\n",
        "# Option 2: set tools at the chat level (applies to all subsequent turns)\n",
        "chat.set_tools([{\"type\": \"file_search\", \"vector_store_ids\": [vs_id]}])\n",
        "resp1 = chat.chat(\"First question\")\n",
        "resp2 = chat.chat(\"Follow-up question\")"
      ],
      "id": "d997a14e",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "::: callout-note\n",
        "**Vector storage is not free.** Currently, storage costs $0.10/GB per day, with the first GB free. See [OpenAI pricing](https://openai.com/api/pricing/) for current rates. Delete vector stores you no longer need from the dashboard.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# Using Websites\n",
        "\n",
        "There are two methods for using a website as context in a chatlas conversation. The right choice depends on whether you need the result to be reproducible.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Method 1: Add the Website to a Vector Store (Recommended)\n",
        "\n",
        "Save the page as a PDF, upload it to a vector store, and query it with `file_search`. This is the most reliable approach because the content is fixed at upload time.\n",
        "\n",
        "Steps:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Open the page in a browser and save it as a PDF.\n",
        "2. Upload the PDF to your vector store (see [Vector Stores](#vector-stores) above).\n",
        "3. Query using `file_search`.\n"
      ],
      "id": "55723a94"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "from chatlas import ChatOpenAI\n",
        "\n",
        "chat = ChatOpenAI(model=model)\n",
        "\n",
        "vs_id = \"your-vector-store-id\"\n",
        "\n",
        "resp = chat.chat(\n",
        "    \"Using ONLY the uploaded page content, answer the following question: \"\n",
        "    \"[your question here]. \"\n",
        "    \"Return your answer as a bulleted list.\",\n",
        "    kwargs={\n",
        "        \"tools\": [{\"type\": \"file_search\", \"vector_store_ids\": [vs_id]}],\n",
        "        \"include\": [\"file_search_call.action.sources\"],  # optional: verify sources\n",
        "    }\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "print(str(resp))"
      ],
      "id": "2ad698f8",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "**Pros:** Deterministic; reusable; indexed once, queried many times; source-traceable.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Cons:** Requires a manual save-to-PDF step; page content is fixed at upload time and will not reflect updates to the live page.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Method 2: Live Web Search\n",
        "\n",
        "Use the `web_search` tool to have the model retrieve and read a live page at query time. Add domain filtering to reduce the chance the model retrieves content from a different site.\n"
      ],
      "id": "5c1d1b7b"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "from chatlas import ChatOpenAI\n",
        "\n",
        "chat = ChatOpenAI(model=model)\n",
        "\n",
        "url = \"https://example.com/page-you-want-to-use\"\n",
        "\n",
        "# Basic web search\n",
        "resp = chat.chat(\n",
        "    f\"Use web search to open and read this specific page:\\n{url}\\n\\n\"\n",
        "    \"Question: [your question here]\\n\\n\"\n",
        "    \"Answer with a bulleted list.\",\n",
        "    kwargs={\n",
        "        \"tools\": [{\"type\": \"web_search\"}],\n",
        "        \"tool_choice\": \"auto\",\n",
        "    },\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "print(str(resp))"
      ],
      "id": "6934fe9f",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "To make results more deterministic with domain filtering (recommended):\n"
      ],
      "id": "52da1a44"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "resp = chat.chat(\n",
        "    f\"Use web search and rely on this page for the answer:\\n{url}\\n\\n\"\n",
        "    \"[Your question here]\",\n",
        "    kwargs={\n",
        "        \"tools\": [\n",
        "            {\n",
        "                \"type\": \"web_search\",\n",
        "                \"filters\": {\n",
        "                    \"allowed_domains\": [\"example.com\"]\n",
        "                },\n",
        "            }\n",
        "        ],\n",
        "        \"tool_choice\": \"auto\",\n",
        "    },\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "print(str(resp))"
      ],
      "id": "be534a41",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "To request sources so you can verify what the model actually read:\n"
      ],
      "id": "72209125"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "resp = chat.chat(\n",
        "    f\"Use web search to answer from this page:\\n{url}\\n\\n\"\n",
        "    \"[Your question here]\",\n",
        "    kwargs={\n",
        "        \"tools\": [{\"type\": \"web_search\"}],\n",
        "        \"tool_choice\": \"auto\",\n",
        "        \"include\": [\"web_search_call.action.sources\"],\n",
        "    },\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "print(str(resp))"
      ],
      "id": "553e6b2b",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "::: callout-note\n",
        "If the model answers without actually searching, make the instruction more explicit: \"Use web search now. Do not answer until the page has been opened.\" Keep the domain filter on.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Web search is not free.** Currently, it costs up to $25 per 1,000 calls. See [OpenAI pricing](https://openai.com/api/pricing/) for current rates.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "**Pros:** Fast; no preprocessing required; reads the live, current version of the page.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Cons:** Not deterministic (page content may change between calls); not reusable across sessions; not guaranteed the model actually reads the target page; not ideal for reproducible research workflows.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# Reusable Online Prompts\n",
        "\n",
        "OpenAI allows you to create and store prompt templates in the dashboard (Dashboard > Prompt), then reference them by ID in your code. The prompt text lives in OpenAI's infrastructure rather than in your repo, and variables are injected at call time.\n",
        "\n",
        "**When this is useful:**\n",
        "\n",
        "- You want to reduce the amount of text submitted on each call\n",
        "- You want a prompt to be shareable across team members without distributing the prompt file\n",
        "- You are iterating on a prompt and want changes to take effect immediately across all callers\n",
        "\n",
        "**Current limitations:**\n",
        "\n",
        "- Not all models are available unless your organization is verified with OpenAI\n",
        "- The prompt text is stored externally and is not version-controlled in your repo unless you maintain a local copy\n",
        "\n",
        "## Basic Usage\n",
        "\n",
        "Create the prompt in the OpenAI dashboard, then reference it by ID:\n"
      ],
      "id": "d945b1e8"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "from openai import OpenAI\n",
        "\n",
        "client = OpenAI()\n",
        "\n",
        "response = client.responses.create(\n",
        "    prompt={\n",
        "        \"id\": \"your-prompt-id\",\n",
        "        \"version\": \"1\",          # pin to a specific version\n",
        "        \"variables\": {           # inject dynamic values\n",
        "            \"variable_name\": \"variable_value\"\n",
        "        }\n",
        "    }\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "print(response.output_text)"
      ],
      "id": "407ed12f",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Adding Follow-up Messages\n",
        "\n",
        "To extend the conversation beyond the initial prompt, include a user message in the `input` field:\n"
      ],
      "id": "cec8ffa0"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "response = client.responses.create(\n",
        "    prompt={\n",
        "        \"id\": \"your-prompt-id\",\n",
        "        \"version\": \"1\",\n",
        "        \"variables\": {\n",
        "            \"variable_name\": \"variable_value\"\n",
        "        }\n",
        "    },\n",
        "    input=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": your_content_variable}],\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "print(response.output_text)"
      ],
      "id": "06e93fe5",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "::: callout-note\n",
        "The `version` field pins your call to a specific version of the stored prompt. If you omit it, the call uses the latest published version, which means prompt changes in the dashboard will immediately affect your code. Pinning to a version is safer for production or reproducible workflows.\n",
        ":::"
      ],
      "id": "48ef1915"
    }
  ],
  "metadata": {
    "kernelspec": {
      "name": "quarto-py",
      "language": "python",
      "display_name": "Python (quarto-py)",
